It’s true - storm drains lead directly to the nearest body of water 🚯 This is something I’ve been wanting to share for awhile, as I hear there’s a lot of confusion around how plastic pollution reaches our Great Lakes and Oceans. So here it is:

70-80% of plastic is transported from land to water via rivers, coastlines, canals and storm drains (the wind also transports pollution, especially microplastics)

20% to 30% comes from marine sources such as fishing nets, lines, ropes, and abandoned vessels (and of course, boaters) 

*I do want to point out that these stats do not account for garbage that has been illegally dumped into our waters

MORE ON STORM DRAINS: 

Stormwater systems were originally created to route rainwater quickly off the streets during a heavy storm. Unfortunately, these systems can also - and currently often - carry pollutants such as pesticides, bacteria and chemicals through city streets and straight to our waters, in addition to fast food wrappers, cigarette butts, styrofoam, sewage overflow, pet waste, used motor oil, fertilizers, paint and construction debris. And unlike the water that goes down a sink or toilet in your home, this water (and all the accompanying trash) goes UNtreated!

MORAL OF THE STORY: 

Don’t litter! Be cognizant of daily actions including what you’re applying to your lawn & how you’re washing your car in the driveway. If you’re near a storm drain, all these fluids, products and trash flow directly into the nearest lake, river or ocean. 

If you’d like to take deeper action, look into adopt-a-drain.org to protect your local drains and directly support waters near you!

I hope you find this explanation helpful in your sustainable living journey! Please share this post so we can spread this much needed awareness and keep our waterways clean! 

And please leave a little 🤍 below if you find value in posts like these! Also - what else have you been wondering about? X

Swipe for the world’s newest, biggest ship or in my opinion — hyper consumerism 🛳️😯 While this @royalcaribbean cruise ship looks like a toy, it’s ready to be booked and will launch in 2024. In a time where our planet is asking us not to abandon Her, this ship literally sets sail away from Her. 

While in Cabo last April, we experienced a @carnival ship in the bay at our favorite location. We love this spot because the sunsets and view are like no other. But this time, what we appreciate so much was blocked by that ship. All we could focus on was the ship’s huge output of black smoke, not to mention it being a total eyesore against the beautiful water, pastel sky and natural rock formations. 

More reasons to think twice about cruise ships: 

• A passenger’s carbon footprint triples while taking a cruise 
• Garbage, fuel and sewage are dumped directly into the ocean by many ships
• Emissions have high levels of nitrogen oxide, linked to acid rain 
• Most ships use heavily toxic oil known as the ‘dirtiest of all fuels’
• These toxic emissions cause health hazards in humans 
• Noise pollution caused by large ship engines disrupt ocean mammals sonar, separating them from their kin and resulting in impaired feeding, increased stress, injury and death
• Even with whale avoidance programs, cruise ships hit whales, injuring and killing them; in the last 5 years NOAA has identified 112 whales who washed ashore with ship related injuries, though FOE reports that 20K whales are killed by cruise and shipping vessels every year

And if you’re asking yourself, ‘what about planes?’ well research shows that cruising emits up to 4 x more CO2 per passenger than flying. 

So as we’re in this season of high consumerism and vacation bookings, let us remember meaningful simplicity that supports our planet and each other 🤍 Happy Holidays! X

Last July, an injured baby green sea turtle was rescued from a beach in Sydney, Australia by Taronga Zoo’s Wildlife Hospital. While in care, the hatchling poo’d plastic for six days 😔 Resident Veterinary Nurse, Sarah Male, explained, “No faeces came out, just pure plastic. It was all different sizes, colours and compositions. Some were hard, some were sharp, and with some, you could tell the plastic had writing on it. This is all some of these poor little things are eating. There’s so much plastic around they’re just consuming it as their first initial food.” 

Every time we choose single-use plastic, that split decision disrupts ecosystems far and wide. These devastating results reach further than we can imagine. 

In 2023, let’s really focus on holding ourselves, companies and governments responsible for adjusting plastic consumption. For reducing disposable plastics is one of the biggest actions we can take for climate change. But this must be done at a collective scale, meaning adjusting our own habits, while calling and writing to companies and officials demanding they do the same. *I recommend including this baby sea turtle’s story to describe why these adjustments are VITAL to planet (and human) health.

WE ARE FACING A SHELTER CRISIS ALL OVER THE U.S. ❤️‍🩹 This overflow is mainly due to two problems: 1) Dogs and cats not being neutered and spayed 2) Now that lockdown is over, people are returning animals back to shelters. PLEASE TAG YOUR FRIENDS + SHARE this very important message from @wolfmotherk9: 

“The single most important thing we need to come to terms with is this:

This is not a "shelter problem."

This is a community problem. 

They are being surrendered and abandoned faster than we can save them. 

They are being bred faster than we can save them. 

They are being given up on faster than we can save them.

If 20 dogs are pulled to rescue, 40 more take their place that same week. 

There is a point where we can no longer keep up with the demand from the public. We have far exceeded that. 

These dogs all had families. They had homes. And in so many cases, whatever that was, whatever that looked like, was so much better than the life the endure at an animal shelter. 

And it may be easy to forget, to go about our days because there are so many things we struggle with in our own lives every day. 

But today I ask you. I beg you. Please think about theirs. 

Please think about their faces as they watch a life go by behind a kennel door with hope. 

Please think about the confusion of losing their home and the life they had, everything they knew, not knowing the odds stacked against them. 

Please think about their final walk to a euthanasia room. Their final breath. And how quickly they are forgotten. 

Over 390,000 dogs every year. Every one had a name. Every one deserves at least a chance. 

Shelters are not dumping grounds. They are not redemption for impulsive decisions or a lack of effort. They exist to support their communities. 
But communities need to support their local shelters too. 

We can all do our part, and it starts at home.”

The Yanomami people are facing a humanitarian crisis in Brazil. Yanomamo territory spans a large area deep in the Amazon rainforest, where 35K Yanomami live in 200 - 250 villages. They remain the most isolated tribe in South America and have built an intricate societal ecosystem - a culture and cosmovision - that entirely functions on living WITH that land. 

In 1980, 40K gold miners rushed Yanomami territory, murdering these people, destroying their villages and  exposing them to diseases in which they had no immunity. 
The Yanomami lost 20% of their population in just seven years. A genocide. 

Current day, President Lula has declared another genocide for the Yanomami as they are still suffering from the same outside elements. Parallel to losing habitat by deforestation for cattle ranching, thousands of illegal miners have carried disease and mercury pollution to Yanomami land. Malaria and malnutrition have taken these people by storm, with proper health care consistently out of reach. 

While becoming a Yanomamo friend and activist, photographer Claudia Andujar captured these communities throughout her last 5 decades. Though her gallery is now closed (I gratefully experienced it on the last day), I’m hoping with this little post, you can catch a glimpse of her fight and call for Yanomami sovereignty in the Amazon rainforest. 

Davi Kopenawa, Yanomami shaman and spokesperson says, “The forest breathes but the white people do not notice. They do not think that it is alive.” 

If you’d like to support the Yanomami and their cry to protect their home in Nature, email Brazil’s government through @survivalinternational - the petition is called ‘An appeal from the Yanomami.’

Thank you @fondationcartier @imoreirasalles @theshedny for organizing a gallery of such importance. 

For planet health equals people health: the ONE undeniable equation of LIFE.

POV: you sort a plan for your food scraps and instantly become part of the climate solution 🙌 PT 1 // 

What is compost? 🍌 Anything that grows will decompose. Composting simply speeds up the process by providing an ideal environment for bacteria, fungi, and other decomposing organisms (worms!) to do their job - breaking down and digesting organics, like leaves and food. This results in a decomposed matter, which looks like fertile garden soil. This is called compost. 

PS: these organisms need 3 elements to do their job - water, light and oxygen. These elements do not reach these organisms at landfill, which is why food does not properly biodegrade while there. 

IMPACT ☀️ Since food is the most prominent material at landfill, developing a plan for your food waste (instead of trashing it) has become very important and impactful!!! 

Please share this video and tag your friends so we can take this simple step resulting in endless impact, together! 

Food should NOT be sent to landfill! X

Sustainable style is pairing your fave tee from 20 yrs ago with a pair of CIRCULAR DENIM jeans 🩵

👖What does circular denim mean? 

1) Used plastic bottles, t-shirts, underwear, knits, jeans and everything in between are recovered from all over the world. They’re broken down and woven together with high tech modal or tencel (made of tree pulp) to make brand new yarn that has less impact on the environment than conventional and even organic cotton. 

2) These fabrics are given that authentic denim look with laser and ozone technologies, without the tremendous use of harmful chemicals and wasted water in traditional washing techniques. 

3) The water that DL 1961 factories do use is recycled, buildings are solar powered and employees work in optimal conditions. 

Basically, manufacturing is completed in vertically integrated facilities while keeping production and materials in a closed loop.

🔄 Closed loop (or circular) means that less resources are extracted from our Earth because more materials are kept in the circular loop of production without being tossed out of this loop and into landfill!
